            AppRoutes = """["/dashboard"]""",
            Tags = """["search","global-search","navigation"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Search Overview\n\nSearch is always in the header bar at the top of every page. It looks through six kinds of things at once, and when the AI helper is turned on it adds a second set of smarter, meaning-based results alongside the plain matches.\n\n### How It Works\n\nThe search box sits in the header, between the breadcrumb trail and the action buttons. As you type, matches drop down grouped by type. It looks through six kinds of things at the same time:\n\n- **Jobs** — matches the job number and title\n- **Customers** — matches the customer name and company name\n- **Parts** — matches the part number and description\n- **Leads** — matches the company name and contact name\n- **Assets** — matches the asset name and serial number\n- **Expenses** — matches the description and category\n\nType at least 2 letters before results appear. Results come up a moment after you stop typing rather than on every keystroke — this keeps things quick even when there's a lot of data.\n\n### Desktop Only\n\nThe search box is a desktop feature. It's hidden on tablet and phone screens to keep the header tidy — on those, open the list page you want (Parts, Customers, Jobs, and so on) and use that page's own filter. On a desktop browser the search box is always in the header, except on the new-hire setup screens, which don't show the usual header.\n\n### Plain Text Matches\n\nThe left side of the results shows the plain text matches. Each one shows a small icon for its type, a main title (job number, part number, customer name, and so on), a bit of context underneath, and a type tag.\n\n**What happens when you click a result.** Clicking a result opens that record's details right over its list — it doesn't just leave you on a plain list page. For example, clicking a part opens the part's details over the Parts list; a job opens over the board. The details stay in the web address, so you can bookmark the link or send it to someone and they'll land in the same place. Five of the six types — jobs, parts, customers, leads, and assets — open their details this way. **Expenses are the exception:** clicking an expense just takes you to the Expenses list, and you open it from there.\n\n### AI Results\n\nWhen the AI helper is turned on, the results split into two columns. The right column shows AI results that match by meaning, not just by exact words.\n\nThe AI column shows:\n- A **written answer** — a short reply to your question in plain language\n- **Matching snippets** — bits of related content, each with a match score as a percentage\n\nThese are handy for questions like 'what jobs involve aluminum machining' or 'which customer ordered the gear housing' — where the exact words might not be written anywhere but the meaning is there in your records.\n\n### Keyboard Shortcuts\n\n- **Ctrl+K** — Jump to the search box from anywhere in the app. It's the fastest way to start without reaching for the mouse, and it's the only keyboard shortcut for search.\n- **Click outside** — Click outside the box and the results close on their own. Your typed text stays put.\n- **Click a result** — Opens that record's details (or, for an expense, its list), clears the box, and closes the results\n\n### When to Use Search\n\n- When you need to find a job fast by its number or title\n- When you're looking up a customer or lead by name\n- When you know a part number but don't want to open the Parts page first\n- When your question is fuzzy and you want the AI helper to find related records\n- When you're hopping between different kinds of things all day","sections":[]}"""
