        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Global Search — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "search-reference",
            Summary = "A deeper look at search: how results are chosen and limited, how matching works, why text and AI results appear at different speeds, how AI results are scored, and why it's desktop only.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/dashboard"]""",
            Tags = """["search","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## How Results Are Chosen and Limited\n\nSearch looks through all six kinds of things — jobs, customers, parts, leads, assets, and expenses — and blends the matches into one list.\n\n- **A fair mix.** Each type gets its own slice so no single type takes over the list. With the usual settings that's a handful of each, with a small guaranteed minimum, so a type with only a few matches still shows up. Within each type, the records you touched most recently come first.\n- **How many you see.** You'll get up to 20 results at once. When there are more than fit, the earlier types in the list (jobs, then customers, then parts, and so on) are favored.\n- **The upper limit.** 20 is the normal amount and 50 is the most it will ever show at once.\n- **At least 2 letters.** Type fewer than 2 letters and you get nothing back. Extra spaces around your words are trimmed off first.\n- **How matching works.** It finds your text anywhere inside the field, and case doesn't matter — searching 'gear' finds 'Gearbox'. Each type checks two things (a job checks its number and title; a part checks its number and description).\n- **Hidden items.** Deleted records never show up, and archived jobs are left out of search too.\n\n## Why Text and AI Results Appear at Different Speeds\n\nThe search box feeds two separate result sets that update at their own pace, so the quick text matches and the slower AI results don't wait on each other:\n\n- **Text matches** refresh a short moment after you stop typing (once you've entered at least 2 letters), so the left column stays snappy.\n- **AI results** wait a little longer before asking, and only ask when the AI helper is actually turned on. That extra pause avoids doing heavy AI work on every keystroke.\n- **Clearing out.** Drop below 2 letters and the AI suggestions, snippets, written answer, and the loading spinner all reset, so clearing the box wipes any leftover AI results.\n- **Shortcuts.** Ctrl+K (or Cmd+K on a Mac) jumps to the box; clicking outside closes the results after a tiny pause so a result click still counts.\n\n## How the AI Results Are Built and Scored\n\nThe AI column matches by meaning rather than exact words.\n\n- **Finding matches.** Your question is turned into a form the AI can compare by meaning; if the AI helper is down, nothing breaks — you just get no AI results and no error. It then pulls back the ten closest snippets from what's been indexed.\n- **The match score.** The percentage you see is a ranking cue, not a precise measurement. The top snippet reads near 100%, the next a little lower, and so on down the list. Treat it as 'this one is a closer match than that one', not an exact figure.\n- **The written answer.** A plain-language answer is written only when there's at least one matching snippet to work from, built from the top few snippets. If writing the answer fails, you still get the snippets — just no summary. The search box always asks for an answer whenever the AI helper is available.\n- **What's searched.** The AI looks across everything that's been indexed, without limiting to one type.\n- **Internal notes are hidden.** Some indexed content is internal documentation that isn't useful to you, so those snippets are dropped from what you see.\n- **Each snippet** shows its text, where in the record it came from, its type, and its match score.\n\n## Why It's Desktop Only\n\nThe search box only shows on desktop-width screens. It's hidden on tablet and phone widths to keep the header uncluttered.\n\n- On tablet or phone there's no search box in the header — open the list page you want (Parts, Customers, Jobs, and so on) and use that page's own filter.\n- It's also hidden on the new-hire setup screens, which don't show the usual header.\n- Hiding the box is only about screen size — Ctrl+K and the search itself still work on narrow screens; only the visible box is tucked away.","sections":[]}"""
        });

